body:
@markusweimer Thank you for your suggestion!
One remaining question is, what should REEF do in response to calling inappropriate API? (For example, calling `requireNodeLabel(final String nodeLabel)` on Mesos runtime.)

I can imagine two paths:
1. Raise an exception.
2. Ignore.

@markusweimer Would you please let me know which way do you prefer?

I have changed implementation of `TransportFactory` to use Tang for choosing protocols.

And I also merged `TransportHttpTest` into `TransportTest`. It was hard to avoid using duplicated codes in separated test because JUnit didn't allowed multiple constructor for any test class and I thought that "changing `tpFactory` by a set method in instance of a test class" is not a good idea.

@taegeonum I would be grateful if you share your idea! Thank you.

@motus Have addressed your second review comments. 
Regarding Avro approach, I agree it would be much cleaner. The reason I use this approach is to build on top of current approach and support backward compatibility as some clients already use it. 
For Avro, need to to figure out how Avro support byte[].

@rogancarr I still don't believe that the regex used (`'[0-9]\.[0-9]+'`) is the right one. 

I've tried running the `change_project_number_readme` part of the script with version `0.17.1` (we're using 3-part version everywhere), and it changed `Org.Apache.REEF.Evaluator, Version=0.15.0.0` to `Org.Apache.REEF.Evaluator, Version=0.17.1.0.0`, and `Org.Apache.REEF.Evaluator.0.15.0` to `Org.Apache.REEF.Evaluator.0.17.1.0` (one extra tailing zero in both cases). 

Your code doesn't flip the major and the first minor versions to new ones, it replaces them with the new version (thus adding an extra part). You need to add one more `\.[0-9]+` to make it work.

This is really not perf testing. As you said, we should have a separate Jira for prop perf testing. Here is really a testing on yarn for the code modified in this JIRA and allow to specify number of containers so that to test scalability. 
For date log, we log date time on different lines that makes me unable to see date time if filter logs by some text. I have changed the logger in .Net to remove the newline. In Java, not sure where it is. 

@markusweimer I have pushed the updated code. Thanks!
